## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The LIS notification provision — and what happens when it does not function — is illustrated by the **2013 Advocate Medical Group breach (referenced in Day 75)** from a different angle. The Advocate breach involved data on unencrypted laptops. But what made the OCR investigation more significant was that the data on those laptops included lab results from a laboratory service provider that Advocate was using — data that had been exchanged through an integration relationship similar to the OpenMRS-LIS interconnection.

The investigation found gaps in Advocate's management of third-party data flows — specifically, that patient data received from the laboratory provider was not subject to the same security controls as data created within Advocate's own systems. The data came in from the lab integration and was accessible to endpoints that were not encrypted.

For the OpenMRS deployment, the equivalent gap would be: lab results arriving through the LIS HL7 integration are written to the OpenMRS RDS database and protected by the RDS encryption controls. The integration endpoint itself — the API connection that receives the HL7 message — must be equally protected. The WAF rules, the security group configuration restricting which source IPs can reach the integration endpoint, and the audit logging of LIS integration events are all part of the security posture for the LIS data flow, not just for the OpenMRS application itself.

The SSP's system interconnection section should document not just that the LIS integration exists but specifically which security controls apply to the integration endpoint — ensuring that ePHI received from the LIS is protected from the moment it enters the authorization boundary.

