## What I Am Still Thinking About

The TOTP authenticator app entry in the TPRM register — rated Low, noted as "not in ePHI data path" — deserves more careful examination than I initially gave it.

The TOTP authenticator app is the second factor in the MFA implementation that protects all OpenMRS user access. If the authenticator app has a vulnerability that allows TOTP codes to be intercepted or predicted, the MFA implementation fails. The app is not in the ePHI data path — it does not store or process patient data — but it is in the authentication security path.

The most significant authenticator app risk is not a software vulnerability — it is user behavior: employees using the same authenticator app account across personal and work purposes, enabling cloud backup of TOTP seeds to personal cloud accounts, or using an authenticator app from an unverified publisher with weak security practices.

The TPRM register entry for the authenticator app should note: "Recommended authenticator apps for OpenMRS MFA: [specific list of approved apps]. Use of unapproved apps, cloud-backup of TOTP seeds to personal accounts, and sharing of authenticator access are prohibited per IS-AC-001." This converts the authenticator app from an unmanaged user choice into a governed security dependency with a defined acceptable use boundary.

This is a policy gap that the TPRM review surfaced — the Access Control Policy (Day 76) specifies TOTP MFA requirement without specifying which authenticator app implementations are acceptable. A brief policy update to IS-AC-001 would close this gap.

